</font></p></td></tr></table><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Preferred Stock</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Series A &#8211; The Series A Preferred Stock is not entitled to dividends, has no liquidation preference and is not convertible into shares of common stock. With respect to voting rights, the shares, collectively, are entitled to that number of votes which shall equal Seventy-five percent (75%) of all eligible votes. <font color="#000000"> There is </font><font color="#000000"> currently 1 shareholder of record of the Company's common stock. </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Series F &#8211; The Series F Preferred Stock is entitled to a quarterly dividend of 5% per annum. The accrued dividend, may, at the option of the holder, be converted into common stock of the Company at a conversion price equal to the closing price of the Company's common stock as of the date of declaration of the dividend (or the most recent trading day if there were no trades on the dividend declaration date). The shares are entitled to a liquidation preference of $0.10 per share, plus unpaid accrued dividends. The shares may be converted into shares of common stock at the option of the holder with a conversion rate of Five (5) shares of Series F Preferred Stock for each share of common stock with no fractional shares being issued. The holder of the Series F Preferred Stock has optional redemption rights as to the principal amount and accrued interest. <font color="#000000"> The </font><font color="#000000"> Series F Preferred Stock </font><font color="#000000"> , </font><font color="#000000"> if fully converted into shares of the Company's common stock would, in the aggregate, be equal to 10,000 shares of common stock. </font><font color="#000000"> There is currently 1 shareholder of the Company </font><font color="#000000"> 's </font><font color="#000000"> Series F Preferred Stock. </font><font color="#000000"> The principal amount of the Series F Preferred Stock is </font><font color="#000000"> $50,000. </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Series G &#8211; The Series G Preferred Stock is not entitled to dividends and has no liquidation preference or redemption rights. The shares may be converted at the option of the holder at a conversion rate of One (1) share of Series G Preferred Stock for each share of common stock with no fractional shares being issued. The shares shall be entitled to one vote for each share. <font color="#000000"> The Series G Preferred Stock </font><font color="#000000"> , </font><font color="#000000"> if fully converted into shares of the Company's common stock would, in the aggregate, be equal to </font><font color="#000000"> 47,696 </font><font color="#000000"> shares of common stock. </font><font color="#000000"> There </font><font color="#000000"> are </font><font color="#000000"> currently </font><font color="#000000"> 2 </font><font color="#000000"> shareholder </font><font color="#000000"> s </font><font color="#000000"> of the Company's </font><font color="#000000"> Series G Preferred Stock </font><font color="#000000"> . </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Series H &#8211; The Series H Preferred Stock is not entitled to dividends and has no liquidation preference or redemption rights. The shares may be converted into shares of common stock at the option of the holder with a conversion rate of Five (5) shares of Series H Preferred Stock for each share of common stock with no fractional shares being issued. </p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">The shares shall be entitled to one vote for each share. <font size="2"><font color="#000000"> The Series H Preferred Stock, if fully converted into shares of the Company's common stock would, in the aggregate, be equal to 1,191 shares of common stock. </font><font color="#000000"> There is currently 1 shareholder of the Company's Series H Preferred Stock. </font></font>   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreak2027f9ad-7412-458a-ac0e-6a4c703faeac" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">15</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Dividend Policy</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">We currently intend to retain any earnings for use in our business, and therefore do not anticipate paying cash dividends in the foreseeable future.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Anti-Takeover Effects Of Provisions of the Articles of Incorporation Authorized and Unissued Stock.</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">The authorized but unissued shares of our common stock are available for future issuance without our stockholders' approval. These additional shares may be utilized for a variety of corporate purposes including but not limited to future public or private offerings to raise additional capital, corporate acquisitions and employee incentive plans. The issuance of such shares may also be used to deter a potential takeover of the Company that may otherwise be beneficial to stockholders by diluting the shares held by a potential suitor or issuing shares to a stockholder that will vote in accordance with the Company's Board of Directors' desires. A takeover may be beneficial to stockholders because, among other reasons, a potential suitor may offer stockholders a premium for their shares of stock compared to the then-existing market price.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b>INTERESTS OF NAMED EXPERTS AND COUNSEL</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">No expert or counsel named in this prospectus as having prepared or certified any part of this prospectus or having given an opinion upon the validity of the securities being registered or upon other legal matters in connection with the registration or offering of the common stock was employed on a contingency basis or had, or is to receive, in connection with the offering, a material interest, in the registrant or any of its parents or subsidiaries.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b>DISCLOSURE OF SEC POSITION OF INDEMNIFICATION FOR SECURITIES ACT LIABILITIES</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Our By-laws include an indemnification provision under which we have agreed to indemnify our directors and officers&nbsp;and hold them harmless from and against claims arising from or related to acts or omissions while a director or officer of the Company, including costs and legal expenses,&nbsp;to the fullest extent permitted by Nevada Law.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Insofar as indemnification for liabilities arising under the Securities Act may be permitted to our directors, officers and controlling persons pursuant to the foregoing provisions, or otherwise, we have been advised that in the opinion of the Securities and Exchange Commission such indemnification is against public policy as expressed in the Securities Act and is, therefore, unenforceable. If a claim for indemnification against such liabilities (other than the payment by us of expenses incurred or paid by a director, officer or controlling person of the Company in the successful defense of any action, suit or proceeding) is asserted by such director, officer or controlling person in connection with the securities being registered) we will, unless in the opinion of our counsel the matter has been settled by controlling precedent, submit to a court of appropriate jurisdiction the question whether such indemnification by us is against public policy as expressed in the Securities Act and will be governed by the final adjudication of such issue. The question whether such indemnification by us is against public policy as expressed in the Securities Act and will be governed by the final adjudication of such issue.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b>EXPERTS</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">The audited financial statements included in this prospectus and elsewhere in the registration statement for the fiscal years ended December 31, <font color="#000000"> 2015, </font> 2014, 2013 and 2012 have been audited by EastWest Accounting Services, LLC of Miami, Florida. The reports of EastWest Accounting Services, LLC are included in this prospectus in reliance upon the authority of this firm as experts in accounting and auditing.   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreakedac1f1e-a033-4509-81c7-b2c2e16069f7" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">16</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b>VALIDITY OF SECURITIES</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">The opinion solely regarding validity of the shares offered herein has been provided by Robert J. Huston III and has been filed with the Registration Statement.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><b><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><font size="2">DESCRIPTION OF BUSINESS</font><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Corporation Organization</font><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p></b><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Escue Energy, Inc. is a Nevada corporation, which was initially formed in Delaware in February 1988 Technicraft Financial Ltd. After several name changes the name was subsequently changed to e-Doorways International, Inc. September 4, 2007. On May 6, 2013, the Company reincorporated in the State of Nevada. On June 23, 2015, the Company's name was changed to Escue Energy, Inc.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><strong>Business of the Company</strong></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Escue Energy, Inc. is a development stage company whose business plan is to manufacture and market Vertical &#8211; Axis Wind Turbines based upon the conceptual designs covered by the United State and Canadian patents which are held by the Company. The Company believes that wind power is a competitive renewable energy source. The demand for power generation by wind turbines is spurred for many reasons. These include:</p><b><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="0ff50dd7-50b4-4426-9a6a-e3e0e7202bee" style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN; MARGIN: auto" face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td width="92%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Public acceptance to the use of renewable energy (wind and solar power).</font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top"></td><td valign="top"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td><p environment from pollution, and to reduce global warming.</font></p></td></tr></table><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">EEI VISIONS AND GOALS</font><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p></b><p style="MARGIN: 0px">EEI has the vision to emerge as an industry leader in environmentally friendly and sustainable energy power&nbsp;business with Small KW &amp; Large MW wind turbines. EEI&nbsp;will bring&nbsp;about significant innovations in wind turbine technology that will make it possible to contribute significantly to the Global Green Energy supply portfolio and improve quality of life and economic opportunities in developing nations.</p><b><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">EEI goals are:</font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="b83a171b-9b5b-4235-bb1c-a0054c202b9e" style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN; MARGIN: auto" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" border="0">    <tr height="15"><td valign="top" width="4%"></td><td valign="top" width="4%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td width="92%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">To build between 2-100 kw units. As the first phase</font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top"></td><td valign="top"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">To identify subcontractors with production facilities to service both domestic and international markets to serve the geographic needs of the market.</font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top"></td><td valign="top"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">To become an eminent supplier of both small and large wind turbine worldwide.</font></p></td></tr></table><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreaka1ae10d1-a625-4595-9157-7d8afaf84e8c" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">17</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b><font size="2">EEI VAWT TECHNOLOGY</font></b><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">EEI's Vertical Axis Wind Turbine (VAWT) technology has been developed from the result of the experiences of our Chief Technology Officer with 45 years of know-how captured from the work performed in the design, engineering, building, construction and operation of numerous electrical power generation systems consisting coal, oil, nuclear and wind. Design verification and validation for wind turbines were obtained with the development of a 4 MW VAWT in 1987 and a 1.5kW VAWT in 2003.</font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> Design verification and validation for the 4 MW VAWT in 1987 was obtained by National Research Council of Canada and Hydro Quebec. The work to verify and validate the design was conducted by Sandia Laboratory, Department of Energy, U.S.A. </font></font><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> </font></font><font color="#000000"> </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><i><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> The work to verify and validate the design for the 1.5kW VAWT in 2003 was conducted by the owner at the factory. Shop tests and operating tests were carried out at the factory, on the prototype demonstration model, to obta </font></font></i><i><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> in design verification and validation of operation and performance. </font></font></i><font color="#000000"> </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> The four proposed prototype demonstration units (2, 10, 20 and 100 KW) are of new updated design, and therefore must be fully </font><font color="#000000"> </font></font><font color="#000000"> re- </font><font size="2"><font color="#000000"><font color="#000000"> tested </font>, and the design and performance of each</font></font><font color="#000000"> of these new </font><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> model </font></font><font color="#000000"> s </font><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> must be verified and validated. </font></font><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">EEI's VAWT incorporate patented innovations designed to meet all the specified criteria for the next generation of wind turbine solutions:</font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="2f2c67c0-cdd5-4aad-bca0-24ffe52604f5" style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt TIMES killing.</font></p></td></tr></table><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><table id="1c48a5c6-cffc-41ad-a635-338066265310" style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt times new roman" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" border="0">    <tr><td valign="top" width="45"></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> (1) </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> Public concerns with respect to "Acceptability" are specifically related to problems encountered with horizontal axis wind turbines, are safety issues, damage or destruction due to lightning strikes, high noise emissions, high maintenance costs, birds and bats kill. </font></p></td></tr><tr><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p></td><td><p 0px"><font color="#000000"> E </font><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> EI wind turbines, with "Patented" straight bladed vertical axis wind turbines, are specifically designed to: </font></font></p></td></tr></table></font>&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol"><table style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt times new roman" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" border="0">    <tr><td width="4%"></td><td width="4%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p></td><td width="4%"><font style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Symbol" color="#000000"> &#183; </font></td><td width="88%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> Address clients' concerns for "Reliability and Availability" regarding wind turbines, and </font></p></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td><font style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Symbol" color="#000000"> &#183; </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> Overcome the technical barriers that produces "Not In My Back Yard" ("NIMBY") syndrome related to wind turbines. </font></p></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> a. </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> EEI VAWT has patented the design for rugged blade construction made with blade-support-struts to reduce and minimize bending stresses during operation. This robust construction offers greater reliability and longer operational life expectancy. VAWT blade not cantilevered. It is supported at both ends. Construction is rugged and does not require sophisticated materials or technology to manufacture, and therefore it is cheaper and easier to fabricate. </font></p></td></tr></table><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><table id="pagebreak57d4b047-2bc5-4058-8920-e45072bf544b" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">18</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="d66891c0-1e8f-4b33-bd85-ee4149c905bd" style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt times new roman" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" border="0">    <tr><td width="4%"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td width="4%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td valign="top" width="4%"><font color="#000000"> b. </font></td><td width="88%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> HAWT design limits operation in high wind, (Over 25 to 30 m/s). Its patented blade design with rugged construction and blade pitch control system, EEI VAWT remains operational in high winds, which yields higher energy production. </font></p></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> c. </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> HAWT units are susceptible for damage from lightning strikes. The very design of horizontal wind turbine, erected in a field, is an invitation for lightning strikes. Since the propeller blades extend much higher than the tower structure, they are subject to frequent lightning strikes, which result in damage and rapid deterioration. EEI VAWT is designed to overcome this problem with structural support system that provides 100% protection lightning protection. </font></p></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> d. </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> Most of the HAWT are noisier in operation, due its higher blade rotational speed. VAWT blade rotational speed is very low, about 1/3rd of HAWT; therefore it is noise-free in operation. [Less than 40 decibels]. </font></p></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> e. </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> Due to the location of the drive train at the ground level, it has easier access for inspection, service and maintenance. Therefore, maintenance time and costs are significantly reduced. VAWT system components are smaller in size and designed for ease of transportation to remote locations. </font></p></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> f. </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> With HAWT units, with the blades in constant motion, flying creatures don't have enough time to recognize a physical obstacle and perish on impact. EEI VAWY units with its caged support structure with shrouds, is less susceptible to problems related to birds and bats kills. </font></p></td></tr></table></font></font>&nbsp;   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><table style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt times new roman" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" border="0">    <tr><td valign="top" width="45"></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> (2) </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> Failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA)&#8212;also "failure modes," plural, in many publications&#8212;was one of the first systematic techniques for failure analysis. It was developed by reliability engineers in the late 1950s to study problems that might arise from malfunctions of military systems. A FMEA is often the first step of a system reliability study. It involves reviewing as many components, assemblies, and subsystems as possible to identify failure modes, and their causes and effects. For each component, the failure modes and their resulting effects on the rest of the system are recorded in a specific FMEA worksheet. </font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> FMEA is an inductive reasoning (forward logic) single point of failure analysis and is a core task in reliability engineering, safety engineering and quality engineering. A successful FMEA activity helps to identify potential failure modes based on experience with similar products and processes - or based on common physics of failure logic. It is widely used in development and manufacturing industries in various phases of the product life cycle. </font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> Fault tree analysis (FTA) is a top down, deductive failure analysis in which an undesired state of a system is analyzed using Boolean logic to combine a series of lower-level events. This analysis method is mainly used in the fields of safety engineering and reliability engineering to understand how systems can fail, to identify the best ways to reduce risk or to determine (or get a feeling for) event rates of a safety accident or a particular system level (functional) failure. </font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> FTA is used in the aerospace, nuclear power and other high-hazard industries. FTA is also used in software engineering for debugging purposes and is closely related to cause-elimination technique used to detect bugs. In aerospace, the more general term "system Failure Condition" is used for the "undesired state" / Top event of the fault tree. </font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top"><font color="#000000"> </font></td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> We utilize these FMEA and FTA analytical tools in the design and engineering process of our VAWT units, to understand how systems can fail, to identify the best ways to reduce risk, to ensure that our products are the best the industry has to offer. </font></p></td></tr></table></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b><font size="2">Market</font></b><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><font size="2"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">We anticipate initial marketing and sale of our products in <font color="#000000"> the United States, Canada, </font>India, Pakistan<font color="#000000"> and </font><font color="#000000"> various countries in </font><font color="#000000"> Africa. </font> With respect to our initial thrust in India, we anticipate significant sales in the sub-continent and other countries with growing demands for energy that lack insufficient infrastructure to meet those increased demands. We believe that our potential customers include governmental agencies as well as private energy providers. Our market could also include the private business sector, farms and individuals seeking to satisfy their own energy needs in the islands and remote locations.</font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</font>&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">In many regions of the world, such as India, China, and South Africa, rather than to purchase the wind turbines from foreign suppliers, there is a desire to acquire the latest state-of-the-art technology of wind turbines locally. Many major manufacturers of wind turbines are currently actively engaged in licensing their wind power technology to the nations interested in developing wind power industry for domestic and export purposes. We expect to also enter into such licensing agreements for our wind power technology. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreakdcdb0e54-8b1f-4621-b6cd-644d033acb4c" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">19</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b><font size="2">Technology: EEI VAWT vs. HAWT (Horizontal &#8211; Axis Wind Turbines)</font></b><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">EEI estimates that the capital cost of the EEI VAWT technology would range from 10% to 20% less than competing HAWT wind turbines.</font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="fb235648-da05-490c-9187-3893ea1f2427" style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN; MARGIN: auto" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" border="0">    <tr height="15"><td valign="top" width="4%"></td><td valign="top" width="4%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td width="92%"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Design constraints and limitations such as size, weight and variability of parts are eliminated since these parts do not have to cater to proprietary nacelle architecture such as those for HAWT. The selection of off-the-shelf components will ensure the continuous availability and rapid procurement of components, facility in managing the logistics of such components and enable local manufacturers and suppliers to participate in the wind-farm deployment. We believe that we will enjoy the following competitive advantages.</font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top"></td><td valign="top"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">The potential for long-term profitability of EEI VAWT will be achieved through the long life span (minimum 30 yrs) of the VAWT. The longer life span will also imply lower reported depreciation expenses.</font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top"></td><td valign="top"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Lower maintenance and equipment costs. Maintainability &amp; Reliability: The VAWT units have all power generation equipment located ground level, which drastically reduces maintenance costs. Under harsh climatic conditions, the VAWT is easy to maintain due the location of equipment inside a building enclosure. VAWT units have better reliability due easy access and maintenance of the equipment located on ground level.</font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top"></td><td valign="top"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">The design specifications deliberately target lower cost off-the-shelf components and materials in order to ensure viability for costs effective operation and maintenance.</font></p></td></tr><tr height="15"><td valign="top"></td><td valign="top"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font face="Symbol">&#183;</font></font><font size="2"></font></p></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">All the power generation equipment in a HAWT unit is located at the top of the structure. Getting to the equipment in the nacelle and working there under harsh climatic conditions is time consuming and difficult, and very expensive. Time (revenue) is wasted due to extensive shut down periods in high wind conditions especially during the winter months. Improvement in maintainability and reliability results in better availability of the unit and therefore more annual energy production.</font></p></td></tr></table><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> For purposes of the comparison of the capital cost of VAWT vs. HAWT, the analysis cost-compared </font><font color="#000000"> each of the types of equipment using the same KW rating, size (same swept area), same equa </font><font color="#000000"> torial height, and same site location. </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> For purposes of calculating </font><font color="#000000"> the minimum of a 30 year life span for the VAWT equipment, we </font><font color="#000000"> have used FMEA and FTA analysis techniques </font><font color="#000000"> , as described </font><font color="#000000"> hereinabove, </font><font color="#000000"> to ensure reliability of the VAWT products. </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b><font size="2">Manufacturing</font></b><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Manufacturing will be provided by&nbsp;sub-contracting fabrication work to selected contractors in various locations and potentially different continents. EEI has already identified selected contractors in Canada<font color="#000000"> (MTN Metals, Inc.) </font> and India <font color="#000000"> who </font><font color="#000000"> , </font><font color="#000000"> when engaged, will be </font><font color="#000000"> able </font> to provide manufacturing, installation, and servicing wind energy systems worldwide.</font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b><font size="2">Sales Channels</font></b><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">EEI wind turbines will be sold to consumers either directly or through authorized distributors. Sales and Marketing will be provided by EEI and through certified dealers, agents, distributors and subsidiaries. <font color="#000000"> At present, we do not have any authorized distributors or certified dealers. </font><font color="#000000"> We intend to engage such sales </font><font color="#000000"> /service </font><font color="#000000"> affiliates after </font><font color="#000000"> proper funding is available. </font> Selected contractors will provide complete "turnkey" installation and on-site service. Certified dealers will receive training in the installation and servicing of EEI wind turbines. Strategic alliances and licensing agreements will be made with manufacturers in the USA and in other countries to effectively supply local markets. International marketing would include licensing arrangements with various countries willing to acquire technology and manufacturing rights.</font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b><font size="2">Incentives and programs</font></b><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Governments are facing increasing pressures to relieve the dependence on fossil fuels and address environmental concerns. Various incentive programs are seeking to promote the development and installation of cleaner energy solutions, especially wind. These incentive programs are usually offered by a power utility/authority as a result of a government or regulatory authority decree or by a government directly. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Categories of incentive programs include: </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="c8437321-3cf4-4565-9c21-50433c2221f7" style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">20</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b><b></b></b>&nbsp;   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b><b>Competition</b></b>   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>&nbsp;   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"></b><p style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt">The Wind Turbine industry participants, primarily in the Horizontal Axis Wind Turbine (HAWT) business include Vestas, GE, Gamesa, Enercon, Suzlon and Siemens. However, because of the size and experience the Company does not deem them to be as direct competitors.   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt">&nbsp;   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt">Several smaller companies which have been successful over the past several years and are active in the Vertical Axis Wind Turbine sector would include Urban Green Energy, Eastern Wind Power, SpinPower Technologies, AIRunner, Helix Wind, Windation Energy Systems, Inc., Capline Systems, UrWind, Shanghai Aeolus Windpower Technologies Co., Ltd., Enargo, Yenny Industry Co., ANew Institute, State of the Art Wind Technologies (SAWT) and Inerjy.   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt">&nbsp;   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt">All of these potential competitors have been in business longer and have much more financial support for their operations. There can be no assurance that we will be able to compete successfully against current and future competitors or that the competitive pressures that we face will not materially adversely affect our business, financial condition and results of operations.   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt">&nbsp;   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><strong>Going Concern Qualification</strong></p><p style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt">&nbsp;   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">Our financial statements have been prepared assuming we will continue as a going concern. The Company has experienced a loss from operations which were brought forward from previous unrelated operations. For the period from inception to <font color="#000000"> December 31 </font><font color="#000000"> , 2015, </font> the Company incurred a net loss of <font color="#000000"> $3,054,848. </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">The Company's financial statements do not include any adjustments to reflect the possible future effects on the recoverability and classification of assets or the amounts and classification of liabilities that may result from the possible inability of the Company to continue as a going concern. This need for additional capital and the uncertainty of obtaining such capital, along with other factors, raise substantial doubt about our ability to continue as a going concern. Our financial statements do not include any adjustment that might result from the outcome of this uncertainty. Assurances cannot be given that adequate financing can be obtained to meet our capital needs.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Patents, Trademarks, Copyrights</b></p><p Adverse legal or regul </font></font><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> atory developments could substantially harm our business. </font></font><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Employees</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">The Company presently has no employees other than its officers and directors.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Properties</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">Our offices are located at 1755 <font color="#000000"> Wittington </font> Place, Suite 340, Dallas, TX 75244. </p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify"><b>Reports to Security Holders</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">We have filed a registration statement on Form S-1 under the Securities Act with the SEC with respect to the securities offered by this prospectus. This prospectus does not include all of the information contained in the registration statement or the exhibits and schedules filed therewith. You should refer to the registration statement and its exhibits for additional information. Whenever we make reference in this prospectus to any of our contracts, agreements or other documents, the references are not necessarily complete and you should refer to the exhibits attached to the registration statement for copies of the actual contract, agreement or other document.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">We will file annual, quarterly and special reports and other information with the Securities and Exchange Commission. You can read these SEC filings and reports, including the registration statement, over the Internet at the SEC's website at http://www.sec.gov. The public may also read and copy materials at the Public Reference Room of the SEC at 100 F Street, NE, Washington DC 20549, on official business days between the hours of 10:00 am and 3:00 pm. Please call the SEC at (800) SEC-0330 for further information on the operations of the public reference facilities. We will provide a copy of our annual report to security holders, including audited financial statements, at no charge upon receipt of your written request to us addressed to us at:</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b>MANAGEMENT'S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND PLAN OF OPERATIONS</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">This section of the Registration Statement includes a number of forward-looking statements that reflect our current views with respect to future events and financial performance. Forward-looking statements are often identified by words like believe, expect, estimate, anticipate, intend, project and similar expressions, or words which, by their nature, refer to future events. You should not place undue certainty on these forward-looking statements. These forward-looking statements are subject to certain risks and uncertainties that could cause actual results to differ materially from our predictions. The following discussion should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and notes thereto included in this Registration Statement.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify"><b><i>Plan of Operation</i></b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">The Company plans to achieve the following milestones through December, 2017.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>First Six Months Commencing January 2016</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">The first phase of our development efforts will be the preparation of blueprints to implement the design of the 4 Vertical-Axis Wind Turbine prototypes. The Company does not currently have engineering <font color="#000000"> staff, but the </font>Company plans to retain independent consulting engineers to develop the blueprints for the building of the prototypes. The Company anticipates that it will spend approximately $1,900,000 to conduct the above<font color="#000000"> </font>mentioned activities. During this time we expect to incur $100,000 in general administrative expense. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreak73b0c681-20fa-4957-a9e0-98abd673a35e" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">22</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>Eighteen Months Commencing July 2016</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Following the engineering of the 4 prototypes, we will secure a third party to manufacture the 4 Vertical Axis Wind Turbine prototypes and thereafter install and conduct initial testing of the prototypes. We estimate expenditures of $2,300,000 related to these efforts. Finally we will conduct operational testing and certification process of the 4 Vertical Axis Wind Turbine prototypes. During this period the Company plans to employ individuals with experience in the testing phase as well as utilize the services of outside independent contractors. We expect to expend $500,000 for the testing and certification process. During this time we expect to expend $200,000 in general administrative expense.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">We are a development stage business and have had no revenue since our formation. There can be no assurance that we will complete the development of the design and manufacture of the 4 VAWT prototypes as we will not be able to generate revenues until the prototypes have been fully tested and certified. Further, there can be no assurance that even if revenues are generated by the business, that those revenues will be sufficient to enable the Company to maintain its operations.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;<b><i>Results of Operations</i></b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">For the fiscal year ended December 31, 2014</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>Revenues</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">For the period from February 1988 (Inception) through December 31, 2014, we did not earn any revenues. We are still a development stage company and do not expect to begin generating revenues until we begin selling our products and services.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>Operating Expenses</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Total operating expenses for the 12 months ended December 31, 2014 and 2013 were $37,603 and $906,765, respectively. The majority of our operating expenses in 2013 were G &amp; A including salaries and consulting fees. Our operating expenses decreased in 2014 due to the reduction in expenditures for salaries and consulting fees.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>Net Gain</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">For the years ended December 31, 2014 and 2013, we realized net gains of $1,088,194 and $3,858,123, respectively. The gains incurred were primarily attributable to gains on settlement of obligations and gains on debt extinguishment.   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreak82493b42-5a0f-4b93-83bd-c10fd5b3157c" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">23</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center">&nbsp;<i>Capital Resources and Liquidity</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Net cash used in operating activities was $19 and ($49,295) for the twelve months period ended December 31, 2014 and 2013, respectively.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Net cash used in investing activities was $0 and $0 the twelve months periods ended December 31, 2014 and 2013, respectively.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Net cash provided by financing activities was $19 and $595 for the twelve months periods ended December 31, 2014 and 2013, respectively.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">We currently rely on cash flows from financing activities to fund our capital expenditures and to support our working capital requirements. We expect that future cash requirements will principally be for capital expenditures and working capital requirements.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">We have generated no revenues since our inception and have incurred an accumulative deficit of $2,593,848 as of December 31, 2014. We anticipate that we will continue to incur net losses in the near term, and we may never be able to achieve profitability. We expect to continue to incur losses for the foreseeable future. In order to achieve profitable operations we need to generate significant revenues from fees earned from the business. We cannot be certain that our business strategies will be successful or that will we generate significant revenues and become profitable. Additionally, we will need to obtain additional public or private equity financings or debt financings in order to continue operations.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">For the Nine months ended September 30, 2015</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>Revenues</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">For the nine months ended September 30, 2015, we did not earn any revenues. We are still a development stage company and do not expect to begin generating revenues until we begin selling our products.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>Operating Expenses</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Total operating expenses for the nine months ended September 30, 2015 were $356,750. The majority of our operating expenses in this period were G &amp; A, including officers' compensation, travel, accounting and legal. </p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>Net Loss</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">For the nine months ended September 30, 2015, we incurred a net loss of $356,750. The losses incurred were primarily due to operating expenses as described above.   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreak99fd576b-4424-4273-8a19-d7c3d1e9621a" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">24</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><i>Capital Resources and Liquidity</i></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Net cash used in operating activities was $-0- for the nine months period ended September 30, 2015.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Net cash used in investing activities was $-0- for the nine months ended September 30, 2015.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Net cash provided by financing activities was $-0- for the nine months ended September 30, 2015.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">In the future we will rely on cash flows from financing activities to fund our capital expenditures and to support our working capital requirements. We expect that future cash requirements will principally be for capital expenditures and working capital requirements.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">We have generated no revenues since our inception and have incurred an accumulative deficit of $2,950,598 as of September 30, 2015. We anticipate that we will continue to incur net losses in the near term, and we may never be able to achieve profitability. We expect to continue to incur losses for the foreseeable future. In order to achieve profitable operations we need to generate significant revenues from fees earned from the business. We cannot be certain that our business strategies will be successful or that will we generate significant revenues and become profitable. Additionally, we will need to obtain additional public or private equity financings or debt financings in order to continue operations.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Off-Balance Sheet Arrangements</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">None.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Description of Property</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">The offices are located at 1755 Willington Place, Suite 340, Dallas, TX 75244. These offices are being provided free of any charges by a non-affiliate.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b>CERTAIN RELATIONSHIPS AND RELATED TRANSACTIONS</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">During the fiscal years, compensation to our officers and directors was paid in both cash and shares of the Company's Common Stock. Reference is made to the Summary Compensation Table for details of these transactions.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center">&nbsp;<b>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Overview</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">The following is a discussion of our program for compensating our named executive officer and directors. Currently, we do not have a compensation committee, and as such, our board of directors, which comprised of our executive officers, are responsible for determining the compensation of our executive officers, and thus in effect sets their own compensation.   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreak2c14df92-a7fd-4b1a-b2fc-4a7880cf54ce" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">25</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Compensation Program Objectives and Philosophy</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">The primary goals of our policy of executive compensation are to attract and retain the most talented and dedicated executive possible, to assure that our executive is compensated effectively in a manner consistent with our strategy and competitive practice and to align executive compensation with the achievement of our short- and long-term business objectives.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">The board of directors considers a variety of factors in determining compensation of our named executive officer, including the particular background and circumstances, such as training and prior relevant work experience, success in attracting and retaining savvy and technically proficient managers and employees, increasing revenues, broadening product line offerings, and managing costs.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">In the near future, we expect that our board of directors will form a compensation committee charged with the oversight of executive compensation plans, policies and programs of our Company and with the full authority to determine and approve the compensation of our Chief Executive Officer.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify"><b>Elements of Compensation</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">Our compensation program for the named executive officer consists primarily of base salary. There is no retirement plan, long-term incentive plan or other such plans. We have not yet obtained a revenue stream with which to fund employee salaries and bonus plans. The base salary we provide is intended to equitably compensate the named executive officer based upon the level of responsibility, complexity and importance of role, leadership and growth potential, and experience.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="justify">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> Our Former CEO </font><font color="#000000"> , </font><font accrued </font><font color="#000000"> in the total amount of $728,351 </font><font color="#000000"> and paid in the form of shares of Common Stock on </font><font color="#000000"> or about March 25, 2014. </font><font color="#000000"> C </font><font color="#000000"> ertain of our current officers </font><font color="#000000"> , including Sohail Quareshi, Madhu Sethi and Shahmir Quareshi </font><font color="#000000"> are employed under Employment Agreements dated </font><font color="#000000"> April 1, 2015, copies of which are attached hereto as Exhibits 10.1, 10.2 and 10.3, respectively. </font><font color="#000000"> Reference is made to Exhibits 10.1, 10.2, 10.3 and 10.5 for a more detailed description of the terms of their employment. </font><font color="#000000"> 0px" align="left">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><table style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; FONT: 10pt times new roman" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" border="0">    <tr><td valign="top" width="45"></td><td valign="top" width="45"><font color="#000000"> (1) </font></td><td><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> Accrued Salaries: Pursuant to the Employment Agreements attached as Exhibits 10.1, 10.2 and 10.3, respectively, the accrued salaries, may, at the option of each individual employee, be taken in whole or in part in the form of common stock of the Company. The amount of stock awarded shall be calculated by dividing the amount of compensation not paid in cash by the average share price during the month of service. The average share price used in the stock calculation will be limited to the higher of the average monthly share price and $0.01. In the event that the employee chooses not to accept stock in lieu of cash compensation, the unpaid cash compensation shall be added to a note payable to the employee with interest thereon payable at the rate of 6% per annum. As of the date hereof, no employee has elected to be paid in common stock of the Company. At this time, it is not the intention of the Company to use proceeds of the Offering to satisfy such accrued obligations. </font></p></td></tr></table></font>&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreak35b309fd-01a0-4600-927c-7644a9ca6b11" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">27</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Employment Agreements</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">On April 1, 2015, the Company entered into Employment Agreements with Sohail Quraeshi, our CEO and President, Madhu Sethi, our COO and Shahmir Quraeshi, our CFO, Secretary and Treasurer. Copies of the Employment Agreements are attached hereto as Exhibits 10.1, 10.2 and 10.3, respectively. <font color="#000000"> On </font><font color="#000000"> January </font><font color="#000000"> 1, </font><font color="#000000"> 2009, the Company entered into a three (3) year Employment Agreement with our then </font><font color="#000000"> CEO, </font><font color="#000000"> Gary Kimmons. </font><font color="#000000"> Pursuant to the </font><font color="#000000"> terms ther </font><font color="#000000"> e </font><font color="#000000"> of, the agreement expired as of January </font><font color="#000000"> 1, </font><font color="#000000"> 2012 </font><font color="#000000"> ; however, compensation was accrued for the </font><font color="#000000"> period </font><font color="#000000"> </font><font color="#000000"> January </font><font color="#000000"> 1, </font><font color="#000000"> 2009 </font><font color="#000000"> through </font><font color="#000000"> January </font><font color="#000000"> 1, </font><font color="#000000"> 2012 and paid in the form of Common Stock of the Company on or </font><font color="#000000"> a </font><font color="#000000"> b </font><font color="#000000"> o </font><font color="#000000"> ut March </font><font color="#000000"> 25, 2014. </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Retirement Benefits</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Currently, we do not provide any company sponsored retirement benefits to the named executive officers.</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Perquisites</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">Historically, we have not provided our named executive officer with any perquisites and other personal benefits. We do not view perquisites as a significant element of our compensation structure, but do believe that perquisites can be useful in attracting, motivating and retaining the executive talent for which we will compete. It is expected that our historical practices regarding perquisites will continue and will be subject to periodic review by our by our board of directors.   <p style="MARGIN: 0px"><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><b>Compensation of Directors</b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2"><font color="#000000"> Pursuant to the Employments Agreements </font><font color="#000000"> attached as Exhibits 10.1, </font><font color="#000000"> and </font><font color="#000000"> 10.2, each of the named employee/officer/directors was entitled to compensation of $5,000 as a director of the Company. </font><font color="#000000"> Each of the </font><font color="#000000"> named individuals has elected to waive such compensation for the period </font><font color="#000000"> beginning as of April 1, 2015 (the effective date of each Employment Agreement) and </font><font color="#000000"> ended December 31, 2015 </font><font color="#000000"> . </font><font color="#000000"> Accordingly, Director Compensation for all periods was zero. </font><font color="#000000"> Each of the directors retains the option to claim such director </font><font color="#000000"> compensation in the future. </font></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font size="2">We did not have a compensation committee during the years ended December 31, <font color="#000000"> 2015, </font>2014, 2013 and 2012. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table for the year then ended. These financial statements are the responsibility of the Company's management. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements based on our audits. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and perform the audits to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement. An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements. An audit also includes assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> In our opinion, the financial statements referred to above present fairly in all material respects, the financial position of <b>Escue Energy, Inc</b>. as of December 31, <b>2015</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;and the results of its operations and its cash flows for the year then ended in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> The accompanying financial statements have been prepared assuming that the Company will continue as a going concern. This Company reports a loss of $37,603 from operations in <b>2015</b>, a negative cash flow of $954,167 from operations in <b>2015</b>, and a stockholders' deficiency of $364,539 as of December 31, <b>2015</b>. This company has earned no revenue in 2015 and until now. We have not come across any serious lapses in internal control. However, the management is informed the need to strengthen the internal controls for reconciling and updating the share registers. The financial statements do not include any adjustments that might result from this deficiency. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> /s/ East West Accounting Services, LLC </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; However, the management is informed the need to strengthen the internal controls for reconciling and updating the share registers. The financial statements do not include any adjustments that might result from this deficiency.</font><font size="2"></font> </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> /s/ East West Accounting Services, LLC </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> Miami, Florida </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> September 27, 2015 </font>&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><table id="pagebreak6c738b44-bbc8-4df3-a08b-5052b5c5b783" class="pagebreak" style="WIDTH: 100%; FONT: 10pt TIMES NEW ROMAN" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">    <tr><td class="hpbhr">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 1px solid; TEXT-ALIGN: center">F-3</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><div style="WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; LINE-HEIGHT: 0px"></div></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px">&nbsp;</p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b><font color="#000000" size="2"> EAST WEST ACCOUNTING SERVICES, LLC </font></b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b><font color="#000000" size="2"> 10030 SW 147 CT. </font></b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b><font color="#000000" size="2"> MIAMI, FL 33196 </font></b></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px" align="center"><b><u><font color="#000000" size="2"> REPORT&nbsp;OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM </font></u></b><font size="2"></font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> To the Board of Directors of: </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> Escue Energy, Inc. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> We have audited the accompanying balance sheets of <b>Escue Energy, Inc</b>. as of December 31, <b>2013</b>, and the related statements of operations, changes in stockholders' deficiency and cash flows for the year then ended. These financial statements are the responsibility of the Company's management. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements based on our audits. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and perform the audits to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement. An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements. An audit also includes assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> In our opinion, the financial statements referred to above present fairly in all material respects, the financial position of <b>Escue Energy, Inc</b>. as of December 31, <b>2013</b>&nbsp;and the results of its operations and its cash flows for the year then ended in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> The accompanying financial statements have been prepared assuming that the Company will continue as a going concern. This Company reports a loss of $906,765 from operations in <b>2013</b>, a net cash flow of $595 in <b>2013</b>, and a stockholders' deficiency of $2,406,881 as of December 31, <b>2013</b>. This company has earned no revenue in 2013 and until now. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> We have not come across any serious lapses in internal control. However, we are of the opinion that the reconciliations, when not completed, may impact the internal controls. During 2012, this company did not reconcile the entries for the share issuance and share transfers in the share registers with the general ledger account. This was informed to the management. Until the reconciliations are complete, we may not be able to assess the deficiencies, if any. As such, the financial statements do not include any adjustments that might result from any deficiency. </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp; </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000" size="2"> /s/ East West Accounting Services, LLC </font></p><p style="MARGIN: 0px"><font color="#000000"> &nbsp;
